Au Optronics, China Steel, Hana, Westfield: Asian Ex-Japan Equity Preview

-- B y   I a n   C .   S a y s o n
-- 
2011-04-17T21:48:44Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-17/au-optronics-hana-westfield-asian-ex-japan-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes today in Asian trading, excluding  Japan .
Stock symbols are in parentheses, and share prices are from the
previous close, unless noted otherwise.  Au Optronics Corp. (2409)  (2409 TT): Sharp Corp. agreed cross-
license patents related to liquid-crystal display panels with
Taiwans’ Au Optronics, the Japanese manufacturer said in a press
statement. The companies will also dismiss all pending legal
actions between them, it said. The stock fell 1 percent to
NT$25.05.  China Steel Corp. (2002)  (2002 TT):  Taiwan ’s largest maker of the
metal will keep June prices unchanged for most products,
Executive Vice President David Du said. The stock fell 0.4
percent to NT$34.85.  Hana Financial Group Inc. (086790)  (086790 KS):  South Korea ’s
fourth-largest financial company said its first-quarter profit
fell 2.6 percent from a year earlier to 389.5 billion won ($357
million). The stock was unchanged at 45,950 won.  Hyundai Heavy Industries Co. (009540 KS): Fred. Olsen
Energy ASA entered into a $615 million turnkey contract with
Hyundai Heavy for the building of a new ultra-deepwater
drillship with scheduled delivery in the third quarter of 2013.
The stock fell 0.9 percent to 533,000 won.  Philippine Long Distance Telephone Co. (TEL)  : The
nation’s largest phone company, also known as PLDT, will keep
Digital Telecommunications Philippines Inc. (DGTL PM) as a
separate company and will maintain its services, PLDT spokesman
Ramon Isberto said. Philippine Telephone, which offered to buy
Digital in a deal valued at 74.1 billion pesos, aims to provide
broadband services to 95 percent of the country in three years,
Isberto said. Having Digitel will make that goal “faster and
cost effective” to achieve, he said. PLDT rose 0.4 percent to
2,350 pesos. Digital gained 0.7 percent to 1.54 pesos.  Westfield Group (WDC)  : The Australian shopping-mall
company is in advanced talks with banks to secure 545 million
pounds ($890 million) of new debt to refinance its Stratford
City development in east  London , the London-based Times reported,
without saying where it got the information. The stock was
unchanged at A$9.08.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Ian C. Sayson in Manila at 
 isayson@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
